transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient experiences persistent feelings of fatigue, frustration, and hopelessness.

evidence.text: You mentioned that these have helped a little, but some days still feel very tough, and you experience feelings of fatigue, frustration, and hopelessness.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient reports that grounding exercises help her feel calmer when she remembers to do them.

evidence.text: The grounding exercises do help me feel a bit calmer, especially when I remember to do them.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient sometimes forgets or feels too overwhelmed to use reminders and journaling as coping strategies.

evidence.text: I try to use the reminders and journal, but I forget or just feel too overwhelmed to do it.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient frequently experiences thoughts of not being good enough, feeling like a failure, and believing she will never catch up or do well enough.

evidence.text: I start thinking that I’m just not good enough. Like, no matter what I do, I still mess up or fall behind. Sometimes I feel like I’m a failure, and that I’ll never catch up or do well enough.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient experiences physical symptoms such as heaviness in her chest, anxiety, upset stomach, numbness, and a foggy or blank mind.

evidence.text: Yeah, I think I feel a kind of heaviness in my chest, like a weight pressing down. Sometimes I get really anxious, and my stomach feels upset. I also feel kind of numb, like I don’t really feel anything, even when I try to focus or do my work. It’s like my mind is just blank or foggy.

transcript_facts.fact_text: Academic pressures, worries about family, and poor sleep are identified as triggers that worsen the patient's distress.

evidence.text: when I have a lot of assignments due or if I think about my family and how I can't support them enough, it gets worse. Also, if I don’t sleep well, everything feels more intense.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient worries about disappointing her family and feels pressure to be perfect.

evidence.text: I worry that I’ll disappoint my family or make them ashamed. Sometimes I feel like I’m just not cut out for this, and I wonder if I should just give up.
I just feel like I have to be perfect all the time, or I’ll let everyone down.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient finds it difficult to stop negative thoughts from recurring and feels that these thoughts are persistent.

evidence.text: Sometimes I just don’t know how to stop those thoughts from taking over. It’s like they’re always there, and I can’t get away from them.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient reports feeling a lack of control over her feelings.

evidence.text: Sometimes I feel like I don’t have any control over these feelings, so any tips would be helpful.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient experiences some relief and calmness when practicing grounding exercises and focusing on the present moment.

evidence.text: It’s kind of calming to just notice these things. I didn’t realize how much I was missing by not paying attention to the present.
I think I’d like to keep practicing this. It feels a little better when I focus on what’s around me instead of my thoughts.

transcript_facts.fact_text: The patient sets goals to use grounding exercises more frequently, journal about her thoughts and feelings, and improve her energy and focus.

evidence.text: I think I want to try using the grounding exercise more when I feel really anxious or sad. Maybe I can also journal about my thoughts and feelings, like I used to. I’d like to understand my feelings better and find ways to handle them without feeling so overwhelmed. I hope I can get a little more energy and focus, too.
